a_7.informal problem: Given two projections of a vector $v$, where the first projection $proj1$ scales the vector by $(2/5, 1/5)$ and results in the vector $(38/5, 19/5)$, and the second projection $proj2$ scales the vector by $(2/13, 3/13)$ and results in the vector $(58/13, 87/13)$, find the original vector $v$. The final answer is $(7, 5)$.

a_8.formal problem:
theorem
fixes v :: "real^2" and proj1 proj2 :: "real^2 \<Rightarrow> real^2"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> v. proj1 v = ((v \<bullet> vector [2, 1]) / ((vector [2, 1]) \<bullet> (vector [2, 1]))) *\<^sub>R (vector [2, 1])"
and h1 : "proj1 v = vector [38/5, 19/5]"
and h2 : "\<forall> v. proj2 v = ((v \<bullet> vector [2, 3]) / ((vector [2, 3]) \<bullet> (vector [2, 3]))) *\<^sub>R (vector [2, 3])"
and h3 : "proj2 v = vector [58/13, 87/13]"
shows  "v = vector [7, 5]"
a_8.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Find the vector $\mathbf{v}$ such that
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix}\]and
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}} \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix}.\] The final Answer is \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}
 ### Proof
 Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}.$ [asy] usepackage("amsmath"); unitsize(0.6 cm); pair P, Q, V; V = (7,5); P = (38/5,19/5); Q = (58/13,87/13); draw((-1,0)--(8,0)); draw((0,-1)--(0,7));
 draw((0,0)--V,Arrow(6)); draw(V--P,dashed); draw((-1,-1/2)--(8,4)); draw((0,0)--P,red,Arrow(6)); draw((-2/3,-1)--(2/3*7,7)); draw(V--Q,dashed); draw((0,0)--Q,red,Arrow(6)); label("$\mathbf{v}$", V, NE);
 label("$\begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix}$", P, SE); label("$\begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix}$", Q, NW); [/asy] Then by the properties of projections, \[\left( \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} \frac{38}{5} \\ \frac{19}{5} \end{pmatrix} \right) \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = 0,\]and
 \[\left( \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix} \right) \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = 0.\]These lead to the equations \[2 \left( x - \frac{38}{5} \right) + \left( y - \frac{19}{5} \right) = 0\]and
 \[2 \left( x - \frac{58}{13} \right) + 3 \left( y - \frac{87}{13} \right) = 0.\]Solving, we find $x = 7$ and $y = 5,$ so $\mathbf{v} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}}.$
 *)

theorem

and h2 : "\<forall> v. proj2 v = ((v \<bullet> vector [2, 3]) / ((vector [2, 3]) \<bullet> (vector [2, 3]))) *\<^sub>R (vector [2, 3])"
and h3 : "proj2 v = vector [58/13, 87/13]"

a_8.informal problem: A vector $v$ in $\mathbb{R}^2$ is projected onto two vectors, $[2, 1]$ and $[2, 3]$. The projections of $v$ onto these two vectors are given as $[38/5, 19/5]$ and $[58/13, 87/13]$ respectively. What is the original vector $v$? The final answer is $[7, 5]$.

 \[\left( \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} \frac{58}{13} \\ \frac{87}{13} \end{pmatrix} \right) \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = 0.\]These lead to the equations \[2 \left( x - \frac{38}{5} \right) + \left( y - \frac{19}{5} \right) = 0\]and

theorem
fixes v :: "real^2"
assumes h0 : "proj (vector [2, 1]) v = vector [38/5, 19/5]"
